---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Anchita Hari — Software Engineer">
  	<main>
		<section class="hero">
			<div class="hero-text">
				<p class="hero-eyebrow">Software Engineer · Building in public</p>
				<h1 class="hero-name">Anchita <em>Hari</em><br>Narayanan</h1>
				<p class="hero-title">Software Engineer</p>
				<p class="hero-bio">
					Backend engineer at Capital One, building with Go and AWS.
					Currently learning in public, starting off with Kubernetes and AI integration.
					Figuring out what kind of engineer I want to become next.
				</p>
				<div class="hero-links">
					<button class="btn-primary" onclick="toggleChat()">Ask me anything</button>
					<a href="/resume.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn-ghost">View resume</a>
					<a href="https://github.com/anchitahari/anchita-dev" target="_blank" class="btn-ghost">View on GitHub</a>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="hero-image">
			<img src="/anchita.png" alt="Anchita Hari Narayanan" />
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="about-section fade-in" id="about">
			<div class="about-sticky">
			<p class="section-label">About</p>
			<h2 class="section-heading">The story so far</h2>
			</div>
			<div class="about-body">
			<p>
				I'm a software engineer based in <strong>McLean, VA</strong>, currently working at Capital One
				in Card Tech, specifically in Card Acquisitions. I contribute to backend systems in <strong>Go and Java</strong>
				and work extensively with <strong>AWS</strong>.
			</p>
			<p>
				After almost four years of engineering, I've realized that the work that I find most energizing isn't 
				just shipping features. It's the moments where I get to <strong>teach, explain, and help others grow</strong> 
				whether that's mentoring teammates, documenting systems clearly, or translating technical decisions into plain language.
			</p>
			<p>
				This site is a project I'm building in public to keep that energy going outside of work. I am <strong>deepening my 
				expertise in Go, learning Kubernetes and AI integration,</strong> and documenting everything along the way so 
				someone else doesn't have to figure it out alone.  
			</p>
			<p>
				Outside of work, I'm a Virginia Tech CS alum who has always been drawn to mentoring and teaching and actively seek 
				those opporutities. My favorite piece of advice to give is <strong>discomfort is a sign you're heading in the right 
				direction</strong>. I'm still learning to follow it myself.
			</p>
			</div>
		</section>
  	</main>
</Layout>